## Current Findings

### Session And Schema Churn

Repeated setup cycles, connections, pack transitions, and schema requests are a
major source of control-plane noise. Helper scripts should reuse sessions and
avoid broad setup work when the editor status beacon and existing manifest are
fresh enough.

The helper path is now better at distinguishing wrapper degradation from direct
bridge health, but the focused Phase 12 scope still showed `17` connections and
`26` pack transitions for one end-to-end smoke. That remains a control-plane
cost problem even though the happy path now succeeds.

### Payload Shaping Gaps

Large `Unity.ManageEditor` and tool-snapshot rows show that compact output is
not yet consistently reducing recorded payload size. This may mean shaping is
missing expensive rows, or telemetry is recording the raw side of the operation
instead of the shaped side.

### Diagnostic Surface Gaps

Phase 11 closed the biggest package/import/Input System read-only gap, and the
compact compatibility view now keeps known benign repeated Input System
integration-test skip lines informational instead of escalating overall status.
The next TSAM diagnostics cluster should cover missing scripts, reference
validation, and import side effects with the same compact/read-first behavior.

### Result Ambiguity

`Unity.RunCommand` must keep failure stage, compilation state, execution state,
and logs internally consistent. Ambiguous stage metadata leads directly to
smaller manual probes and slower recovery.

Structured `ExecutionResult.ReturnResult(...)` payloads should stay compact,
prefer detail refs when large, and remain available even when execution logs
warnings or errors.

The helper-driven play-mode path now preserves structured `returnedData`
correctly when it can prove direct Lens health and healthy play-mode state,
instead of forcing a failing idle wait first.

